o set visibility to private\n\n[01:17] and then open this repo in cursor. So I\n\n[01:20] will be building this in cursor, but you\n\n[01:22] can also use cloud codeex or any other\n\n[01:25] AI coding agent that you prefer. The\n\n[01:27] only thing you need to do if you''re not\n\n[01:28] using cursor is to simply tag this\n\n[01:31] workflow file and the commands files\n\n[01:34] that we''ll be using in the prompt. So\n\n[01:36] I''m going to start simple and just tell\n\n[01:38] cloudset to create a sales ops agent\n\n[01:40] with two built-in tools IPython\n\n[01:43] interpreter and persistent shell tool.\n\n[01:45] The reason we need these two tools is\n\n[01:47] because the agent must be able to\n\n[01:48] actually discover local files and then\n\n[01:50] run them in Python in order to use this\n\n[01:53] new approach. And both of these tools\n\n[01:55] are already available in our framework.\n\n[01:57] So let''s hit send and wait until the\n\n[01:59] agent is built. Now, I''m also going to\n\n[02:01] tell it to add another sales ops direct\n\n[02:04] MCP agent for comparison later. By the\n\n[02:07] way, if you''re building a more\n\n[02:08] sophisticated MVP, there is also a new\n\n[02:10] PRD command which you can use to have\n\n[02:13] more control over your agent structure.\n\n[02:15] Okay, now here''s where the magic\n\n[02:17] happens. I added a new special command\n\n[02:19] called MCP code execution, which you can\n\n[02:22] use to add MCP servers to an agent using\n\n[02:25] this new pattern. So all you need to do\n\n[02:28] in order to use this is simply tag this\n\n[02:29] command and then tell cursor which MCP\n\n[02:32] servers to use. So I recommend finding\n\n[02:34] the exact MCP servers you need on GitHub\n\n[02:37] or elsewhere and then adding links back\n\n[02:40] into cursor. Now simply hit send again.\n\n[02:42] So this command already describes to\n\n[02:44] cursor pretty much everything it needs\n\n[02:46] to know about this new pattern and even\n\n[02:48] links the blog post and all the other\n\n[02:50] resources that it might need. This way\n\n[02:52] cursor can reliably add it using the\n\n[02:54] same structure that they proposed in\n\n[02:56] this blog post. So you can see how now\n\n[02:58] cursor created the server directory with\n\n[03:00] the code for our servers and then it\n\n[03:02] proceeds to creating the code for\n\n[03:04] individual tools. You might also need to\n\n[03:06] authenticate the server if it''s using or\n\n[03:09] off. Now it proceeds to creating files\n\n[03:11] for individual tools. So you can see how\n\n[03:13] now this server is made here directly in\n\n[03:16] code instead of passing this description\n\n[03:19] and the arguments directly into the\n\n[03:21] agents context window. Cursor saves this\n\n[03:23] description in code. So then whenever\n\n[03:26] our agent needs to use this tool, it\n\n[03:28] will simply read this file and then it\n\n[03:30] will see the whole description and the\n\n[03:33] arguments in order to use this tool. So\n\n[03:35] this way again we don''t load all the\n\n[03:37] tools. We only load one tool that cursor\n\n[03:39] actually needs to use. Okay. So in total\n\n[03:41] cursor created 15 tools for notion MCP\n\n[03:44] server and four tools for Google drive.\n\n[03:46] It has also already tested notion MCP\n\n[03:49] server. However, it wasn''t able to test\n\n[03:51] Google Drive because of missing\n\n[03:52] credentials. So make sure you provide\n\n[03:54] all the credentials up front. Do not\n\n[03:56] repeat my mistake. Typically you can\n\n[03:57] find instructions on how to get the\n\n[03:59] credentials inside the readme of your\n\n[04:01] MCP server. Then you can simply tell\n\n[04:03] cursor to retest the server. Then you\n\n[04:05] will also be required to authenticate.\n\n[04:07] Okay. Now the next step is to write\n\n[04:09] instructions. So for writing\n\n[04:10] instructions, I also recommend you use\n\n[04:12] this write instructions command and then\n\n[04:14] simply tag the agent that you want to\n\n[04:16] create the instructions for. Then cursor\n\n[04:18] is going to ask you a few questions to\n\n[04:20] properly define the context for your\n\n[04:22] agent. So make sure you answer all these\n\n[04:24] questions carefully and the most\n\n[04:25] important one is the process and\n\n[04:27] workflow. So prompting is key with this\n\n[04:30] technique and in order for this agent to\n\n[04:31] use it effectively, it must clearly\n\n[04:33] understand the process. So basically the\n\n[04:35] first step is to always check available\n\n[04:37] skills in the Mnt skills folder. I''ll\n\n[04:40] explain why Mnt folder later then it\n\n[04:43] should use the skill if such a skill is\n\n[04:44] found for a specific task. If no skills\n\n[04:47] are found then it should only read one\n\n[04:49] tool that it needs to use and after that\n\n[04:51] it should combine all such tools in\n\n[04:53] order to complete a task successfully\n\n[04:55] and finally provide suggestions for new\n\n[04:57] skills to be added. So you can play\n\n[05:00] around with this workflow. This is just\n\n[05:01] a general process from the blog post.\n\n[05:04] But I think there are a lot of\n\n[05:05] innovations just from prompting the\n\n[05:07] agent. So let''s hit send. And in the\n\n[05:09] meantime, I also want to add MCPS using\n\n[05:12] the direct MCP approach to the other\n\n[05:14] sales ops direct MCP agent. So for this,\n\n[05:17] we also have a command. It''s simply add\n\n[05:19] MCP. And then I''m also just going to\n\n[05:21] link the two MCP servers that we added\n\n[05:23] to the previous agent. Okay, now we are\n\n[05:26] ready to test this agency. So let''s open\n\n[05:28] it in terminal and just run python\n\n[05:30] agency.py. Pi. Now let''s perform a\n\n[05:33] simple test. Let me ask it what''s on\n\n[05:35] this notion page.\n\n[05:39] So first the agent listed the mount\n\n[05:41] skills directory. Then it read the fetch\n\n[05:45] tool file to understand all the\n\n[05:46] parameters. And it seems like it ran\n\n[05:49] into some issues with the imports.\n\n[05:52] However, then at the end I was still\n\n[05:54] able to read this page by performing\n\n[05:57] this fetch tool request and it provided\n\n[06:00] me with the preview of this file. Okay.\n\n[06:03] Now the next step is to deploy this\n\n[06:04] agent and then we''ll compare it with the\n\n[06:06] direct MCP approach. So let''s push our\n\n[06:08] changes to GitHub and now let''s go to\n\n[06:11] agency. So hit create new agency and\n\n[06:13] then find this new agent repo. Then\n\n[06:16] provide your keys from the end file. And\n\n[06:19] now let''s wait until our agency is\n\n[06:21] deployed. Okay. So now our agency is\n\n[06:23] deployed. So let''s actually test it. So\n\n[06:26] let me put it in a custom GPT. Let''s\n\n[06:28] select both agents\n\n[06:31] and let''s deploy it. Now let me send\n\n[06:33] this task from Andropics blog post to\n\n[06:35] copy the transcript from Google Drive\n\n[06:38] and paste it into a page in notion.\n\n[06:41] Let''s see if it''s actually going to be\n\n[06:42] able to do it.\n\n[06:45] Seems like it did read way too many\n\n[06:47] files. Like for example, it even read\n\n[06:49] this server file which it definitely\n\n[06:51] doesn''t need.\n\n[06:55] And now finally it tells me that it was\n\n[06:57] in fact able to do this. So let''s check\n\n[07:00] the notion page.\n\n[07:04] And yes indeed we now get this\n\n[07:06] transcript from our Q&A call exactly\n\n[07:09] like it was on Google Drive. And also at\n\n[07:12] the end it proposed to create this new\n\n[07:14] skill for itself. So let me tell it to\n\n[07:16] save the skill. So you can see that the\n\n[07:18] agent told me that it saved the skills\n\n[07:20] in the mount skills directory. So the\n\n[07:23] reason you need to use this mount\n\n[07:24] directory is because we now have\n\n[07:26] persistent storage on our platform. And\n\n[07:28] without this feature, it would not be\n\n[07:30] possible to allow your agents to evolve\n\n[07:32] and build their own skills over time. So\n\n[07:34] in this mount directory essentially your\n\n[07:37] agents can now save files like this and\n\n[07:39] reference them across different chats.\n\n[07:41] So now if I start a new chat and then\n\n[07:43] send the same prompt again, the agent\n\n[07:45] should take a lot less time and just use\n\n[07:48] the skill in order to do this task\n\n[07:50] quickly. So you can see how now it found\n\n[07:52] the skill and read the file and the\n\n[07:54] agent was able to still perform the same\n\n[07:56] task.\n\n[07:58] Okay, now let''s quickly test another\n\n[08:00] agent that uses direct MCP approach. So\n\n[08:04] now you can see how this agent is\n\n[08:05] reading this whole transcript with the G\n\n[08:07] drive read file tool which hopefully is\n\n[08:10] not going to cost me too much and it\n\n[08:12] also read the notion page and now it''s\n\n[08:15] trying to add this transcript to this\n\n[08:17] notion page. But as you can see it has\n\n[08:19] to manually type this whole thing which\n\n[08:21] is definitely going to cost me too much\n\n[08:23] now. So you can see how it''s literally\n\n[08:26] spending like probably tens of thousands\n\n[08:28] of tokens for no reason simply because\n\n[08:31] it had to do one simple copy paste\n\n[08:33] operation. Finally, it''s finished. So\n\n[08:36] now let''s take a look at the traces and\n\n[08:38] analyze the costs. So tracing is enabled\n\n[08:41] by default in our framework. And in\n\n[08:43] order to see the traces, all you need to\n\n[08:45] do is go to dashboard and then simply\n\n[08:47] find the name of your agency. Okay, so\n\n[08:49] let''s see this sales ops direct MCP\n\n[08:52] agent. And in total, this agent consumed\n\n[08:55] 32,000 tokens. This is just insane. And\n\n[08:59] most of these tokens