INSERT INTO "mcp_actions" VALUES('d5cade04-d2e3-4c24-adf7-f506fe586f4b','5dd28c5e-208f-4d10-902c-c6eb0fd17f10','youtube-transcript','get_youtube_transcript',3,0,NULL,NULL,'{"params":{"videoUrl":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BOl05zmQjOg"},"result":{"videoId":"BOl05zmQjOg","videoUrl":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BOl05zmQjOg","transcript":"[00:00] What is the future of the product cycle\n\n[00:01] with AI? This is a question I get asked\n\n[00:04] all the time with product teams. Hey, my\n\n[00:06] name is Diane and I''m the founder of the\n\n[00:08] design project. I have designed for\n\n[00:10] Crocs and MercedesBenz. I''ve been a solo\n\n[00:13] designer for five startups and today we\n\n[00:16] work with over 50 B2B SAS companies\n\n[00:19] working with teams that have been\n\n[00:20] acquired by Slack, Nvidia, and Mr.\n\n[00:22] Beast. I''m on the cutting edge of\n\n[00:24] speeding up design to dev handoff using\n\n[00:26] AI to generate front-end code. Today, I\n\n[00:29] take my Figma designs, I build front-end\n\n[00:31] code with cloud code and cursor, and I\n\n[00:33] deliver directly into my customers repo.\n\n[00:36] What we''ll cover today, setting up cloud\n\n[00:38] code with cursor, connecting GitHub and\n\n[00:40] Figma MCP. We''re going to build out a\n\n[00:43] feature within cloud code and cursor,\n\n[00:45] and I''m going to answer questions I get\n\n[00:47] from teams that want to implement this\n\n[00:49] process. So, why claude code within\n\n[00:52] cursor? I have tested Figma make, v0,\n\n[00:55] lovable, all of them. This is my only\n\n[00:58] recommendation. Figma to claude code\n\n[01:00] within cursor. Why? Because claude code\n\n[01:03] is better. It cuts out the middleman and\n\n[01:05] it goes directly into the codebase that\n\n[01:07] your devs are using. Okay. Step one is\n\n[01:10] get repo access. Your designers, PMs,\n\n[01:13] anyone on the product team needs to get\n\n[01:15] invited to the company repo from your\n\n[01:17] devs. The biggest concern here is devs\n\n[01:20] say, \"I don''t want my designer PM\n\n[01:22] messing up my code.\" Which is completely\n\n[01:24] valid. The solution is to create a\n\n[01:26] separate branch that the product team\n\n[01:28] can work off of. They work off this\n\n[01:29] branch. They won''t break the code and\n\n[01:31] there''s peace of mind. So now let''s get\n\n[01:34] started. Here''s the server up and\n\n[01:36] running.\n\n[01:37] Here''s cloud code within cursor. And\n\n[01:39] here''s my Figma file.\n\n[01:42] First, I''m going to make sure it has\n\n[01:44] access. Do you see my Figma?\n\n[01:50] Do you see my Figma?\n\n[01:53] Now, what I need to do is build a button\n\n[01:57] here that is going to open the sidebar I\n\n[01:59] created. I''m going to prompt it\n\n[02:05] create a button that looks like this\n\n[02:07] button class and put it next to this\n\n[02:09] button class. So, basically I''m telling\n\n[02:10] it create a button that looks exactly\n\n[02:12] like this next to this button. Let''s see\n\n[02:15] what it does.\n\n[02:19] the button next to the call actions\n\n[02:23] button.\n\n[02:24] Both buttons visible side by side. I\n\n[02:26] should keep both buttons replaced. Keep\n\n[02:29] both buttons.\n\n[02:34] Okay, here we go. Add context. I would\n\n[02:37] need to clean this up, make it\n\n[02:39] capitalized, but it added the button,\n\n[02:41] which is great. Okay, now I''m going to\n\n[02:43] prompt it.\n\n[02:45] Based on my Figma selection, create a\n\n[02:47] sidebar that slides out from the right\n\n[02:49] side of the screen when clicking the add\n\n[02:50] context button. Make sure all fonts and\n\n[02:53] colors adhere to the design. For all\n\n[02:55] components, make sure each state is\n\n[02:57] fully functional. Make sure to follow\n\n[02:58] the exact programming language the\n\n[03:00] codebase already uses. So what''s really\n\n[03:03] important here is to start to build a\n\n[03:05] design system because once you build a\n\n[03:07] design system, it is going to be able to\n\n[03:09] replicate those components and reuse\n\n[03:11] them everywhere and you won''t have to\n\n[03:13] keep tweaking because it is already\n\n[03:15] pulling the direct code that you''ve\n\n[03:17] created.\n\n[03:20] Okay,\n\n[03:22] let''s go check it out.\n\n[03:28] Let''s see how it looks compared to this.\n\n[03:32] Pretty good,\n\n[03:35] functional.\n\n[03:38] So, there you have it. Built this whole\n\n[03:40] sidebar connecting to the button with\n\n[03:43] prompting.\n\n[03:45] Great. Now, the last thing I want to do\n\n[03:47] is commit this code.\n\n[03:55] So, I''m going to go up here,\n\n[03:58] press commit. It''s going to be pushed to\n\n[04:00] the repo for the devs to review. Great.\n\n[04:03] Done. Here are the most common questions\n\n[04:06] I get from founders, PMs, head of\n\n[04:08] product that want to start this process.\n\n[04:10] Question one, what percentage does a\n\n[04:13] design need to be done before passing it\n\n[04:15] to code? I would say about 80 to 90%\n\n[04:18] done. It doesn''t need interactions. It\n\n[04:20] just needs the components and the layout\n\n[04:22] on the screen because cloud code is not\n\n[04:25] a mind readader. So by taking that Figma\n\n[04:28] design, you''re going to be able to get\n\n[04:29] it to a place where cloud code can pick\n\n[04:32] it up, start to build those\n\n[04:33] interactions, and then from there you\n\n[04:35] can tweak as necessary.\n\n[04:37] Question two, once designs are\n\n[04:39] implemented, what does that iteration\n\n[04:41] cycle look like? So the designers can\n\n[04:44] continue to prompt and work within cloud\n\n[04:45] code and cursor or they can go back to\n\n[04:48] Figma. It''s dependent on the project. I\n\n[04:51] suggest if it''s already in cloud code,\n\n[04:54] you continue to prompt it there to get\n\n[04:55] it to where you need. This process takes\n\n[04:58] some time. There is a learning curve. So\n\n[05:01] just suggest to your team is to stick\n\n[05:03] with it. Question three, can I trust the\n\n[05:05] code? This is why I suggest cloud code\n\n[05:08] because it is the code that most dev\n\n[05:10] teams are using to build on top of. I\n\n[05:14] also suggest that engineers still review\n\n[05:16] the PRD. They need to check for\n\n[05:18] performance, code standards, security,\n\n[05:20] everything like that. Again, this is\n\n[05:22] really great for front-end code.\n\n[05:25] Backend, I still suggest that the devs\n\n[05:28] play with the back end. Question four,\n\n[05:31] what''s the designer''s workload versus\n\n[05:33] AI''s workload? Are designers just\n\n[05:35] pressing buttons? Now, no. Designers are\n\n[05:37] still thinking deeply about the UX and\n\n[05:40] the process up front. They''re still\n\n[05:42] putting together those Figma designs.\n\n[05:44] They''re using AI for research.\n\n[05:46] absolutely as they should to speed\n\n[05:48] things up. But once they get that Figma\n\n[05:50] in place, they basically are able to\n\n[05:52] replace that front-end dev that you\n\n[05:55] need. The designer is still designing,\n\n[05:57] they''re also shipping, and AI is an\n\n[05:59] execution tool, not the brain. So, thank\n\n[06:02] you for watching my video. Please\n\n[06:04] subscribe to the channel to get more\n\n[06:06] insights from product teams.","wordCount":1134}}','2025-11-13T21:57:26.353Z');
