INSERT INTO "mcp_actions" VALUES('13377f71-58d4-43b7-96e8-456eb7432fb3','5dd28c5e-208f-4d10-902c-c6eb0fd17f10','youtube-transcript','get_youtube_transcript',3,0,NULL,NULL,'{"params":{"videoUrl":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D4ImbDGFgIM"},"result":{"videoId":"D4ImbDGFgIM","videoUrl":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D4ImbDGFgIM","transcript":"[00:00] Entropic just dropped a blog post that\n\n[00:02] changes how we think about building AI\n\n[00:05] agents. In this latest update, they\n\n[00:07] showed how MCPS might have been the\n\n[00:10] wrong abstraction for AI agents after\n\n[00:13] all. And what''s funny is that I actually\n\n[00:15] came to the same conclusion and\n\n[00:17] implemented the alternative approach\n\n[00:19] that they suggested a week before this\n\n[00:21] blog post came out. And the difference\n\n[00:24] in performance was striking. the agent\n\n[00:27] not only produced significantly better\n\n[00:29] results and worked more autonomously,\n\n[00:31] but it also consumed 98% less tokens.\n\n[00:36] And so in this video, I''m going to break\n\n[00:38] down this blog post. I''m going to\n\n[00:39] explain the core problems with MCPS and\n\n[00:43] what you should do instead to build more\n\n[00:45] effective AI agents. Let''s dive right\n\n[00:48] in. Okay, code execution with MCPS. So,\n\n[00:52] let''s start at the very beginning. The\n\n[00:54] model context protocol is an open\n\n[00:56] standard for connecting AI agents to\n\n[00:59] external systems. So what exactly are\n\n[01:02] MCPs? Well, under the hood, MCPs are\n\n[01:05] just APIs. It''s literally just that. The\n\n[01:09] only difference is that a standard API\n\n[01:11] is typically developed for a developer\n\n[01:13] to use, while an MCP is developed for an\n\n[01:16] AI agent to use. On a technical level,\n\n[01:19] there are not that many differences. MCP\n\n[01:22] provides a universal protocol.\n\n[01:23] Developers implement MCP once in their\n\n[01:25] agent and it unlocks an entire ecosystem\n\n[01:28] of integrations. So the biggest\n\n[01:30] breakthrough with MCPS isn''t really the\n\n[01:33] protocol itself. It''s the fact that it\n\n[01:35] became the standard across the entire\n\n[01:37] industry. So because everyone is now\n\n[01:40] using this protocol to build tools for\n\n[01:41] their AI agents, it means that we\n\n[01:44] developers can now easier collaborate\n\n[01:46] and share our tools with others.\n\n[01:49] However, as the number of connected\n\n[01:51] tools grows, loading all tool\n\n[01:53] definitions up front and passing\n\n[01:55] intermediate results through the context\n\n[01:56] window slows down the agents and\n\n[01:59] increases the cost. So this is the first\n\n[02:02] problem with MCPS, excessive token\n\n[02:05] consumption. And typically this problem\n\n[02:07] originates from two things. The first\n\n[02:10] one is that tool definitions overload\n\n[02:13] the context window. So if you connect\n\n[02:15] your agent to an MCP, typically that MCP\n\n[02:19] contains like 20 to 30 different tools\n\n[02:23] and many people don''t connect just one\n\n[02:25] MCP. They typically connect like five or\n\n[02:27] six different MCPS and so each and every\n\n[02:30] tool that you connected to this MCP\n\n[02:32] server contains a specific description\n\n[02:35] and parameters in order to use that\n\n[02:38] tool. And so even if the agent only is\n\n[02:40] planning to use one tool, it still has\n\n[02:43] all this context from all the other\n\n[02:45] tools from all the MCP servers that you\n\n[02:47] have connected in its context window.\n\n[02:50] And this first of all increases the\n\n[02:52] cost. Second increases the latency and\n\n[02:55] third potentially increases the number\n\n[02:57] of hallucinations. And the second reason\n\n[03:00] MCPS increase the token consumption is\n\n[03:02] because of the intermediate tool\n\n[03:04] results. And so for example, if your\n\n[03:06] agent is trying to retrieve a transcript\n\n[03:09] from Google Drive, this tool might\n\n[03:11] return like 50 thousands of tokens and\n\n[03:14] larger documents may even exceed the\n\n[03:16] context window limits. While the agent\n\n[03:19] might not necessarily need all that\n\n[03:21] data, it might only need like the first\n\n[03:23] paragraph of the transcript instead. And\n\n[03:26] so what they propose is essentially code\n\n[03:29] execution that allows the agent to call\n\n[03:32] MCP servers on the go. So the way they\n\n[03:35] propose we structure this is by creating\n\n[03:37] separate folders where inside each\n\n[03:40] folder we have a subfolder for each MCP\n\n[03:42] server and inside that subfolder we have\n\n[03:45] the specific tools as simple TypeScript\n\n[03:48] files. So then whenever the agent\n\n[03:50] actually needs to use a tool it can\n\n[03:52] simply import that tool from that folder\n\n[03:54] and then simply call this tool in code.\n\n[03:57] And so using this approach we don''t pass\n\n[03:59] all these tools into the agents context\n\n[04:02] window. we only pass one tool that the\n\n[04:04] agent actually needs to use. And\n\n[04:07] secondly, now the agent no longer has to\n\n[04:09] read the entire transcript. It can save\n\n[04:11] that transcript as a variable or into\n\n[04:14] the file system and then it can only\n\n[04:16] fetch the necessary details. Like in\n\n[04:19] this example, it doesn''t even have to\n\n[04:20] read the content of the transcript. It\n\n[04:22] can simply take this transcript and\n\n[04:24] without even reading it, send it to\n\n[04:27] Salesforce MCP server. So this is just\n\n[04:29] the first benefit of using code instead\n\n[04:32] of MCP servers. The next one is that now\n\n[04:35] you can also have progressive\n\n[04:37] disclosure. So this means that you can\n\n[04:38] now have as many MCP servers as you\n\n[04:41] want. You''re no longer limited by\n\n[04:43] context of the MCP server at all. You\n\n[04:46] can literally provide your agent with\n\n[04:48] thousands of MCP servers and the agent\n\n[04:50] can simply use another search tools tool\n\n[04:53] to help itself to discover the MCP that\n\n[04:56] it actually needs right now. Next, it\n\n[04:58] also has some privacy benefits. So, this\n\n[05:01] is extremely common with those larger\n\n[05:03] enterprise clients who don''t want to\n\n[05:05] expose their sensitive data to\n\n[05:07] thirdparty model providers like\n\n[05:09] Anthropic or OpenAI. And if you connect\n\n[05:12] their APIs to an agent using MCPS,\n\n[05:15] obviously all this data will be\n\n[05:16] automatically exposed. However, if the\n\n[05:19] agent is using MCP servers in code, you\n\n[05:21] can add a special harness to the agent\n\n[05:24] and essentially automatically anonymize\n\n[05:27] any data that the agent is trying to\n\n[05:29] fetch. So like for example, you can\n\n[05:30] modify this get sheet tool and ensure\n\n[05:33] that it returns all the emails\n\n[05:35] anonymized just like this. And last but\n\n[05:38] not least, it also provides state\n\n[05:40] persistence and skills. So this in my\n\n[05:42] opinion is the most game-changing\n\n[05:44] benefit of this approach. So essentially\n\n[05:47] if the agent doesn''t have a specific\n\n[05:49] skill it can create a function for\n\n[05:51] itself and then it can save it in one of\n\n[05:53] the folders and after that it can use it\n\n[05:56] later as needed. This way the agent can\n\n[05:59] essentially evolve which is closely\n\n[06:01] related to this new concept of skills\n\n[06:03] that cloth has recently introduced. So\n\n[06:06] that''s it for the primary benefits. I\n\n[06:07] think this blog post has done a really\n\n[06:09] good job explaining the benefits of this\n\n[06:11] approach but I didn''t really explain all\n\n[06:13] the limitations. So the first one is\n\n[06:15] that it''s simply less reliable. So if\n\n[06:18] your agent has to generate code every\n\n[06:20] single time it needs to call a tool,\n\n[06:22] then there are more chances that it''s\n\n[06:24] going to make a mistake. And secondly,\n\n[06:26] it also increases your infrastructure\n\n[06:28] overhead. So if you want to use this\n\n[06:30] approach, you first have to set up a\n\n[06:32] sandbox, an independent secure\n\n[06:34] environment for the agent where it can\n\n[06:37] safely execute code and also interact\n\n[06:40] with other APIs. So setting this up\n\n[06:43] requires quite a bit of work but we have\n\n[06:45] already done this if you want to use it\n\n[06:46] on our platform. Okay. So in conclusion\n\n[06:49] I want to just mention that everything\n\n[06:51] that you see on the screen is just code\n\n[06:54] and files. And so that''s why I think\n\n[06:56] that this approach makes so much more\n\n[06:59] sense. Agents have become increasingly\n\n[07:01] good at generating code in the last\n\n[07:03] couple years. And so it only makes sense\n\n[07:05] for us to stop really creating these\n\n[07:07] abstractions on top of other\n\n[07:09] abstractions for our agents because they\n\n[07:11] can simply generate code on a go. You\n\n[07:13] see, every single abstraction that you\n\n[07:15] add to your agent significantly reduces\n\n[07:18] the autonomy of that agent. And the\n\n[07:20] primary reason of having an agent in the\n\n[07:23] first place is so that it could\n\n[07:24] autonomously execute your tasks for you.\n\n[07:27] So does that mean that we will never use\n\n[07:29] MCP servers again? Well, definitely no.\n\n[07:31] Like for example, for customer support\n\n[07:33] and where the API isn''t that complex and\n\n[07:36] you don''t need to do any\n\n[07:37] transformations, you just need to send a\n\n[07:39] customer support ticket, it definitely\n\n[07:40] still makes sense. But for other more\n\n[07:43] complex use cases, this approach is\n\n[07:45] certainly a lot more powerful and this\n\n[07:48] is exactly what I''m going to be using\n\n[07:50] primarily moving forward for all our\n\n[07:52] agents. So, if you want to see how\n\n[07:54] exactly we''ve already built one of the\n\n[07:57] agents like this that can connect to any\n\n[07:59] API without even using MCP servers, make\n\n[08:01] sure you watch this video next. Thank\n\n[08:03] you and see you next","wordCount":1578}}','2025-11-14T07:45:18.467Z');
